First your questions. 

The argument of `getRandom(Set&lt;Integer&gt; setInt)` is not being used. You are creating a new set anyway inside the function. That is why passing `null` still works. So might as well change it to:

```
public static Set&lt;Integer&gt; getRandom(){

    Set&lt;Integer&gt; setInt = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
```

Your loop is just saying you want to do the loop 4 times. If it happens to generate the same number, the set will omit the duplicate, so you could end up with less. 

What you really need is a List there, so that duplicates are not eliminated.

```
public static List&lt;Integer&gt; getRandom(){

  List&lt;Integer&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(4);
```

Also, you should put the `Random` outside. If you are creating a new one each time inside the loop, it will lose its pseudo-random sequence. 

Finally, there is a better way if you decide to use Java 8. 

```
Random random = new Random();

return Stream.generate(() -&gt; random.nextInt(10))
             .limit(4)
             .collect(Collectors.toList());
```

`Set` has no order and contains no duplicates - just like in mathematics. `Random` is something what you instantiate once in a program, definitely not in the middle of a loop.

